classes.name: MappingCollection
classes.description: A collection of deprecated mappings.

classes.name: PredicateMapping
classes.description: A deprecated predicate mapping object contains the deprecated predicate and an example of the rewiring that should be done to use a qualified statement in its place.

classes.name: OntologyClass
classes.description: a concept or class in an ontology, vocabulary or thesaurus. Note that nodes in a biolink compatible KG can be considered both instances of biolink classes, and OWL classes in their own right. In general you should not need to use this class directly. Instead, use the appropriate biolink class. For example, for the GO concept of endocytosis (GO:0006897), use bl:BiologicalProcess as the type.
comments: This is modeled as a mixin. 'ontology class' should not be the primary type of a node in the KG. Instead you should use an informative bioloink category, such as AnatomicalEntity (for Uberon classes), ChemicalSubstance (for CHEBI or CHEMBL), etc

Note that formally this is a metaclass. Instances of this class are instances in the graph, but can be the object of 'type' edges. For example, if we had a node in the graph representing a specific brain of a specific patient (e.g brain001), this could have a category of bl:Sample, and by typed more specifically with an ontology class UBERON:nnn, which has as category bl:AnatomicalEntity

examples.description: the class 'brain' from the Uberon anatomy ontology

classes.name: Annotation
classes.description: Biolink Model root class for entity annotations.

classes.name: QuantityValue
classes.description: A value of an attribute that is quantitative and measurable, expressed as a combination of a unit and a numeric value

classes.name: Attribute
classes.description: A property or characteristic of an entity. For example, an apple may have properties such as color, shape, age, crispiness. An environmental sample may have attributes such as depth, lat, long, material.

classes.name: ChemicalRole
classes.description: A role played by the molecular entity or part thereof within a chemical context.

classes.name: PhenotypicSex
classes.description: An attribute corresponding to the phenotypic sex of the individual, based upon the reproductive organs present.

classes.name: GenotypicSex
classes.description: An attribute corresponding to the genotypic sex of the individual, based upon genotypic composition of sex chromosomes.

classes.name: SeverityValue
classes.description: describes the severity of a phenotypic feature or disease

classes.name: PathognomonicityQuantifier
classes.description: A relationship quantifier between a variant or symptom and a disease, which is high when the presence of the feature implies the existence of the disease

classes.name: Entity
classes.description: Root Biolink Model class for all things and informational relationships, real or imagined.

classes.name: NamedThing
classes.description: a databased entity or concept/class

classes.name: RelationshipType
classes.description: An OWL property used as an edge label

classes.name: TaxonomicRank
classes.description: A descriptor for the rank within a taxonomic classification. Example instance: TAXRANK:0000017 (kingdom)

classes.name: OrganismTaxon
classes.description: A classification of a set of organisms. Example instances: NCBITaxon:9606 (Homo sapiens), NCBITaxon:2 (Bacteria). Can also be used to represent strains or subspecies.

classes.name: Event
classes.description: Something that happens at a given place and time.

classes.name: StudyResult
classes.description: A collection of data items from a study that are about a particular study subject or experimental unit (the  'focus' of the Result) - optionally with context/provenance metadata that may be relevant to the interpretation of this data as evidence.
notes: The data/metadata included in a Study Result object are typically a subset of data from a larger study data set, that are selected by a curator because they may be useful as evidence for deriving knowledge about a specific focus of the study. The notion of a 'study' here is defined broadly to include any research activity at any scale that is aimed at generating knowledge or hypotheses. This may include a single assay or computational analyses, or a larger scale clinical trial or experimental research investigation.

classes.name: Study
classes.description: a detailed investigation and/or analysis

classes.name: StudyVariable
classes.description: a variable that is used as a measure in the investigation of a study

classes.name: CommonDataElement
classes.description: A Common Data Element (CDE) is a standardized, precisely defined question, paired with a set of allowable  responses, used systematically across different sites, studies, or clinical trials to ensure consistent  data collection. Multiple CDEs (from one or more Collections) can be curated into Forms.  (https://cde.nlm.nih.gov/home)

classes.name: ConceptCountAnalysisResult
classes.description: A result of a concept count analysis.

classes.name: ObservedExpectedFrequencyAnalysisResult
classes.description: A result of a observed expected frequency analysis.

classes.name: RelativeFrequencyAnalysisResult
classes.description: A result of a relative frequency analysis.

classes.name: TextMiningResult
classes.description: A result of text mining.

classes.name: ChiSquaredAnalysisResult
classes.description: A result of a chi squared analysis.

classes.name: Agent
classes.description: person, group, organization or project that provides a piece of information (i.e. a knowledge association)

classes.name: InformationContentEntity
classes.description: a piece of information that typically describes some topic of discourse or is used as support.

classes.name: Dataset
classes.description: an item that refers to a collection of data from a data source.

classes.name: DatasetDistribution
classes.description: an item that holds distribution level information about a dataset.

classes.name: DatasetVersion
classes.description: an item that holds version level information about a dataset.

classes.name: DatasetSummary
classes.description: an item that holds summary level information about a dataset.

classes.name: ConfidenceLevel
classes.description: Level of confidence in a statement

classes.name: EvidenceType
classes.description: Class of evidence that supports an association

classes.name: InformationResource
classes.description: A database or knowledgebase and its supporting ecosystem of interfaces  and services that deliver content to consumers (e.g. web portals, APIs,  query endpoints, streaming services, data downloads, etc.). A single Information Resource by this definition may span many different datasets or databases, and include many access endpoints and user interfaces. Information Resources include project-specific resources such as a Translator Knowledge Provider, and community knowledgebases like ChemBL, OMIM, or DGIdb.

classes.name: Publication
classes.description: Any published piece of information. Can refer to a whole publication, its encompassing publication (i.e. journal or book) or to a part of a publication, if of significant knowledge scope (e.g. a figure, figure legend, or section highlighted by NLP). The scope is intended to be general and include information published on the web, as well as printed materials, either directly or in one of the Publication Biolink category subclasses.

classes.name: Book
classes.description: This class may rarely be instantiated except if use cases of a given knowledge graph support its utility.

classes.name: Serial
classes.description: This class may rarely be instantiated except if use cases of a given knowledge graph support its utility.

classes.name: PhysicalEssenceOrOccurrent
classes.description: Either a physical or processual entity.

classes.name: PhysicalEssence
classes.description: Semantic mixin concept.  Pertains to entities that have physical properties such as mass, volume, or charge.

classes.name: PhysicalEntity
classes.description: An entity that has material reality (a.k.a. physical essence).

classes.name: Occurrent
classes.description: A processual entity.

classes.name: ActivityAndBehavior
classes.description: Activity or behavior of any independent integral living, organization or mechanical actor in the world

classes.name: Activity
classes.description: An activity is something that occurs over a period of time and acts upon or with entities; it may include consuming, processing, transforming, modifying, relocating, using, or generating entities.

classes.name: Procedure
classes.description: A series of actions conducted in a certain order or manner

classes.name: Phenomenon
classes.description: a fact or situation that is observed to exist or happen, especially one whose cause or explanation is in question

classes.name: Device
classes.description: A thing made or adapted for a particular purpose, especially a piece of mechanical or electronic equipment

classes.name: StudyPopulation
classes.description: A group of people banded together or treated as a group as participants in a research study.

classes.name: SubjectOfInvestigation
classes.description: An entity that has the role of being studied in an investigation, study, or experiment

classes.name: MaterialSample
classes.description: A sample is a limited quantity of something (e.g. an individual or set of individuals from a population, or a portion of a substance) to be used for testing, analysis, inspection, investigation, demonstration, or trial use. [SIO]

classes.name: PlanetaryEntity
classes.description: Any entity or process that exists at the level of the whole planet

classes.name: GeographicLocation
classes.description: a location that can be described in lat/long coordinates

classes.name: GeographicLocationAtTime
classes.description: a location that can be described in lat/long coordinates, for a particular time

classes.name: ThingWithTaxon
classes.description: A mixin that can be used on any entity that can be taxonomically classified. This includes individual organisms; genes, their products and other molecular entities; body parts; biological processes

classes.name: MolecularEntity
classes.description: A molecular entity is a chemical entity composed of individual or covalently bonded atoms.

classes.name: ChemicalEntity
classes.description: A chemical entity is a physical entity that pertains to chemistry or biochemistry.

classes.name: SmallMolecule
classes.description: A small molecule entity is a molecular entity characterized by availability in small-molecule databases of SMILES, InChI, IUPAC, or other unambiguous representation of its precise chemical structure; for convenience of representation, any valid chemical representation is included, even if it is not strictly molecular (e.g., sodium ion).

classes.name: ChemicalMixture
classes.description: A chemical mixture is a chemical entity composed of two or more molecular entities.

classes.name: NucleicAcidEntity
classes.description: A nucleic acid entity is a molecular entity characterized by availability in gene databases of nucleotide-based sequence representations of its precise sequence; for convenience of representation, partial sequences of various kinds are included.

classes.name: MolecularMixture
classes.description: A molecular mixture is a chemical mixture composed of two or more molecular entities with known concentration and stoichiometry.

classes.name: ComplexMolecularMixture
classes.description: A complex molecular mixture is a chemical mixture composed of two or more molecular entities with unknown concentration and stoichiometry.

classes.name: BiologicalProcessOrActivity
classes.description: Either an individual molecular activity, or a collection of causally connected molecular activities in a biological system.

classes.name: MolecularActivity
classes.description: An execution of a molecular function carried out by a gene product or macromolecular complex.

classes.name: BiologicalProcess
classes.description: One or more causally connected executions of molecular functions

classes.name: ProcessedMaterial
classes.description: A chemical entity (often a mixture) processed for consumption for nutritional, medical or technical use. Is a material entity that is created or changed during material processing.

classes.name: Drug
classes.description: A substance intended for use in the diagnosis, cure, mitigation, treatment, or prevention of disease
comments: The CHEBI ID represents a role rather than a substance

classes.name: Food
classes.description: A substance consumed by a living organism as a source of nutrition

classes.name: OrganismAttribute
classes.description: describes a characteristic of an organismal entity.

classes.name: PhenotypicQuality
classes.description: A property of a phenotype

classes.name: GeneticInheritance
classes.description: The pattern or 'mode' in which a particular genetic trait or disorder is passed from one generation to the next, e.g. autosomal dominant, autosomal recessive, etc.

classes.name: OrganismalEntity
classes.description: A named entity that is either a part of an organism, a whole organism, population or clade of organisms, excluding chemical entities

classes.name: Virus
classes.description: A virus is a microorganism that replicates itself as a microRNA and infects the host cell.

classes.name: LifeStage
classes.description: A stage of development or growth of an organism, including post-natal adult stages

classes.name: IndividualOrganism
classes.description: An instance of an organism. For example, Richard Nixon, Charles Darwin, my pet cat. Example ID: ORCID:0000-0002-5355-2576

classes.name: PopulationOfIndividualOrganisms
classes.description: A collection of individuals from the same taxonomic class distinguished by one or more characteristics.  Characteristics can include, but are not limited to, shared geographic location, genetics, phenotypes.

classes.name: DiseaseOrPhenotypicFeature
classes.description: Either one of a disease or an individual phenotypic feature. Some knowledge resources such as Monarch treat these as distinct, others such as MESH conflate.  Please see definitions of phenotypic feature and disease in this model for their independent descriptions.  This class is helpful to enforce domains and ranges   that may involve either a disease or a phenotypic feature.

classes.name: Disease
classes.description: A disorder of structure or function, especially one that produces specific  signs, phenotypes or symptoms or that affects a specific location and is not simply a  direct result of physical injury.  A disposition to undergo pathological processes that exists in an  organism because of one or more disorders in that organism.

classes.name: PhenotypicFeature
classes.description: A combination of entity and quality that makes up a phenotyping statement. An observable characteristic of an  individual resulting from the interaction of its genotype with its molecular and physical environment.

classes.name: BehavioralFeature
classes.description: A phenotypic feature which is behavioral in nature.

classes.name: AnatomicalEntity
classes.description: A subcellular location, cell type or gross anatomical part

classes.name: CellularComponent
classes.description: A location in or around a cell

classes.name: ChemicalEntityOrGeneOrGeneProduct
classes.description: A union of chemical entities and children, and gene or gene product. This mixin is helpful to use when searching across chemical entities that must include genes and their children as chemical entities.

classes.name: ChemicalEntityOrProteinOrPolypeptide
classes.description: A union of chemical entities and children, and protein and polypeptide. This mixin is helpful to use when searching across chemical entities that must include genes and their children as chemical entities.

classes.name: MacromolecularMachineMixin
classes.description: A union of gene locus, gene product, and macromolecular complex. These are the basic units of function in a cell. They either carry out individual biological activities, or they encode molecules which do this.

classes.name: GeneOrGeneProduct
classes.description: A union of gene loci or gene products. Frequently an identifier for one will be used as proxy for another

classes.name: Gene
classes.description: A region (or regions) that includes all of the sequence elements necessary to encode a functional transcript. A gene locus may include regulatory regions, transcribed regions and/or other functional sequence regions.

classes.name: GeneProductMixin
classes.description: The functional molecular product of a single gene locus. Gene products are either proteins or functional RNA molecules.

classes.name: GeneProductIsoformMixin
classes.description: This is an abstract class that can be mixed in with different kinds of gene products to indicate that the gene product is intended to represent a specific isoform rather than a canonical or reference or generic product. The designation of canonical or reference may be arbitrary, or it may represent the superclass of all isoforms.

classes.name: MacromolecularComplex
classes.description: A stable assembly of two or more macromolecules, i.e. proteins, nucleic acids, carbohydrates or lipids, in which at least one component is a protein and the constituent parts function together.

classes.name: NucleosomeModification
classes.description: A chemical modification of a histone protein within a nucleosome octomer or a substitution of a histone with a variant histone isoform. e.g. Histone 4 Lysine 20 methylation (H4K20me), histone variant H2AZ substituting H2A.

classes.name: Genome
classes.description: A genome is the sum of genetic material within a cell or virion.

classes.name: Exon
classes.description: A region of the transcript sequence within a gene which is not removed from the primary RNA transcript by RNA splicing.

classes.name: Transcript
classes.description: An RNA synthesized on a DNA or RNA template by an RNA polymerase.

classes.name: Polypeptide
classes.description: A polypeptide is a molecular entity characterized by availability in protein databases of amino-acid-based sequence representations of its precise primary structure; for convenience of representation, partial sequences of various kinds are included, even if they do not represent a physical molecule.

classes.name: Protein
classes.description: A gene product that is composed of a chain of amino acid sequences and is produced by ribosome-mediated translation of mRNA

classes.name: ProteinIsoform
classes.description: Represents a protein that is a specific isoform of the canonical or reference protein. See https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4114032/

classes.name: ProteinDomain
classes.description: A conserved part of protein sequence and (tertiary) structure that can evolve, function, and exist independently of the rest of the protein chain. Protein domains maintain their structure and function independently of the proteins in which they are found. e.g. an SH3 domain.

classes.name: PosttranslationalModification
classes.description: A chemical modification of a polypeptide or protein that occurs after translation.  e.g. polypeptide cleavage to form separate proteins, methylation or acetylation of histone tail amino acids,  protein ubiquitination.

classes.name: NucleicAcidSequenceMotif
classes.description: A linear nucleotide sequence pattern that is widespread and has, or is conjectured to have, a biological significance. e.g. the TATA box promoter motif, transcription factor binding consensus sequences.

classes.name: RNAProductIsoform
classes.description: Represents a protein that is a specific isoform of the canonical or reference RNA

classes.name: SiRNA
classes.description: A small RNA molecule that is the product of a longer exogenous or endogenous dsRNA, which is either a bimolecular duplex or very long hairpin, processed (via the Dicer pathway) such that numerous siRNAs accumulate from both strands of the dsRNA. SRNAs trigger the cleavage of their target molecules.

classes.name: GeneGroupingMixin
classes.description: any grouping of multiple genes or gene products

classes.name: GeneFamily
classes.description: any grouping of multiple genes or gene products related by common descent

classes.name: Genotype
classes.description: An information content entity that describes a genome by specifying the total variation in genomic sequence and/or gene expression, relative to some established background

classes.name: Haplotype
classes.description: A set of zero or more Alleles on a single instance of a Sequence[VMC]

classes.name: SequenceVariant
classes.description: A sequence_variant is a non exact copy of a sequence_feature or genome exhibiting one or more sequence_alteration.

alt_descriptions.description: An entity that describes a single affected, endogenous allele. These can be of any type that matches that definition
A contiguous change at a Location

comments: This class is for modeling the specific state at a locus. A single DBSNP rs ID could correspond to more than one sequence variants (e.g CIViC:1252 and CIViC:1253, two distinct BRCA2 alleles for rs28897743)

classes.name: Snv
classes.description: SNVs are single nucleotide positions in genomic DNA at which different sequence alternatives exist

classes.name: ReagentTargetedGene
classes.description: A gene altered in its expression level in the context of some experiment as a result of being targeted by gene-knockdown reagent(s) such as a morpholino or RNAi.

classes.name: ClinicalAttribute
classes.description: Attributes relating to a clinical manifestation

classes.name: ClinicalMeasurement
classes.description: A clinical measurement is a special kind of attribute which results from a laboratory observation from a subject individual or sample. Measurements can be connected to their subject by the 'has attribute' slot.

classes.name: ClinicalModifier
classes.description: Used to characterize and specify the phenotypic abnormalities defined in the phenotypic abnormality sub-ontology, with respect to severity, laterality, and other aspects

classes.name: ClinicalCourse
classes.description: The course a disease typically takes from its onset, progression in time, and eventual resolution or death of the affected individual

classes.name: Onset
classes.description: The age group in which (disease) symptom manifestations appear

classes.name: ClinicalEntity
classes.description: Any entity or process that exists in the clinical domain and outside the biological realm. Diseases are placed under biological entities

classes.name: ClinicalFinding
classes.description: this category is currently considered broad enough to tag clinical lab measurements and other biological attributes taken as 'clinical traits' with some statistical score, for example, a p value in genetic associations.

classes.name: SocioeconomicAttribute
classes.description: Attributes relating to a socioeconomic manifestation

classes.name: Case
classes.description: An individual (human) organism that has a patient role in some clinical context.

classes.name: Cohort
classes.description: A group of people banded together or treated as a group who share common characteristics. A cohort 'study' is a particular form of longitudinal study that samples a cohort, performing a cross-section at intervals through time.

classes.name: ExposureEvent
classes.description: A (possibly time bounded) incidence of a feature of the environment of an organism that influences one or more phenotypic features of that organism, potentially mediated by genes

classes.name: GenomicBackgroundExposure
classes.description: A genomic background exposure is where an individual's specific genomic background of genes, sequence variants or other pre-existing genomic conditions constitute a kind of 'exposure' to the organism, leading to or influencing an outcome.

classes.name: PathologicalEntityMixin
classes.description: A pathological (abnormal) structure or process.

classes.name: PathologicalProcess
classes.description: A biologic function or a process having an abnormal or deleterious effect at the subcellular, cellular, multicellular, or organismal level.

classes.name: PathologicalProcessExposure
classes.description: A pathological process, when viewed as an exposure, representing a precondition, leading to or influencing an outcome, e.g. autoimmunity leading to disease.

classes.name: PathologicalAnatomicalStructure
classes.description: An anatomical structure with the potential of have an abnormal or deleterious effect at the subcellular, cellular, multicellular, or organismal level.

classes.name: PathologicalAnatomicalExposure
classes.description: An abnormal anatomical structure, when viewed as an exposure, representing an precondition, leading to or influencing an outcome, e.g. thrombosis leading to an ischemic disease outcome.

classes.name: DiseaseOrPhenotypicFeatureExposure
classes.description: A disease or phenotypic feature state, when viewed as an exposure, represents an precondition, leading to or influencing an outcome, e.g. HIV predisposing an individual to infections; a relative deficiency of skin pigmentation predisposing an individual to skin cancer.

classes.name: ChemicalExposure
classes.description: A chemical exposure is an intake of a particular chemical entity.

classes.name: ComplexChemicalExposure
classes.description: A complex chemical exposure is an intake of a chemical mixture (e.g. gasoline), other than a drug.

classes.name: DrugExposure
classes.description: A drug exposure is an intake of a particular drug.

classes.name: DrugToGeneInteractionExposure
classes.description: drug to gene interaction exposure is a drug exposure is where the interactions of the drug with specific genes are known to constitute an 'exposure' to the organism, leading to or influencing an outcome.

classes.name: Treatment
classes.description: A treatment is targeted at a disease or phenotype and may involve multiple drug 'exposures', medical devices and/or procedures

classes.name: BioticExposure
classes.description: An external biotic exposure is an intake of (sometimes pathological) biological organisms (including viruses).

classes.name: GeographicExposure
classes.description: A geographic exposure is a factor relating to geographic proximity to some impactful entity.

classes.name: EnvironmentalExposure
classes.description: A environmental exposure is a factor relating to abiotic processes in the environment including sunlight (UV-B), atmospheric (heat, cold, general pollution) and water-born contaminants.

classes.name: BehavioralExposure
classes.description: A behavioral exposure is a factor relating to behavior impacting an individual.

classes.name: SocioeconomicExposure
classes.description: A socioeconomic exposure is a factor relating to social and financial status of an affected individual (e.g. poverty).

classes.name: Outcome
classes.description: An entity that has the role of being the consequence of an exposure event. This is an abstract mixin grouping of various categories of possible biological or non-biological (e.g. clinical) outcomes.

classes.name: PathologicalProcessOutcome
classes.description: An outcome resulting from an exposure event which is the manifestation of a pathological process.

classes.name: PathologicalAnatomicalOutcome
classes.description: An outcome resulting from an exposure event which is the manifestation of an abnormal anatomical structure.

classes.name: DiseaseOrPhenotypicFeatureOutcome
classes.description: Physiological outcomes resulting from an exposure event which is the manifestation of a disease or other characteristic phenotype.

classes.name: BehavioralOutcome
classes.description: An outcome resulting from an exposure event which is the manifestation of human behavior.

classes.name: HospitalizationOutcome
classes.description: An outcome resulting from an exposure event which is the increased manifestation of acute (e.g. emergency room visit) or chronic (inpatient) hospitalization.

classes.name: MortalityOutcome
classes.description: An outcome of death from resulting from an exposure event.

classes.name: EpidemiologicalOutcome
classes.description: An epidemiological outcome, such as societal disease burden, resulting from an exposure event.

classes.name: SocioeconomicOutcome
classes.description: An general social or economic outcome, such as healthcare costs, utilization, etc., resulting from an exposure event

classes.name: Association
classes.description: A typed association between two entities, supported by evidence
comments: This is roughly the model used by biolink and ontobio at the moment

classes.name: ContributorAssociation
classes.description: Any association between an entity (such as a publication) and various agents that contribute to its realisation

classes.name: GenotypeToGenotypePartAssociation
classes.description: Any association between one genotype and a genotypic entity that is a sub-component of it

classes.name: GenotypeToGeneAssociation
classes.description: Any association between a genotype and a gene. The genotype have have multiple variants in that gene or a single one. There is no assumption of cardinality

classes.name: GenotypeToVariantAssociation
classes.description: Any association between a genotype and a sequence variant.

classes.name: GeneToGeneAssociation
classes.description: abstract parent class for different kinds of gene-gene or gene product to gene product relationships. Includes homology and interaction.

classes.name: GeneToGeneHomologyAssociation
classes.description: A homology association between two genes. May be orthology (in which case the species of subject and object should differ) or paralogy (in which case the species may be the same)

classes.name: GeneToGeneFamilyAssociation
classes.description: Set membership of a gene in a family of genes related by common evolutionary ancestry usually inferred by sequence comparisons. The genes in a given family generally share common sequence motifs which generally map onto shared gene product structure-function relationships.

classes.name: GeneExpressionMixin
classes.description: Observed gene expression intensity, context (site, stage) and associated phenotypic status within which the expression occurs.

classes.name: GeneToGeneCoexpressionAssociation
classes.description: Indicates that two genes are co-expressed, generally under the same conditions.

classes.name: PairwiseGeneToGeneInteraction
classes.description: An interaction between two genes or two gene products. May be physical (e.g. protein binding) or genetic (between genes). May be symmetric (e.g. protein interaction) or directed (e.g. phosphorylation)

classes.name: PairwiseMolecularInteraction
classes.description: An interaction at the molecular level between two physical entities

classes.name: CellLineToEntityAssociationMixin
classes.description: An relationship between a cell line and another entity

classes.name: CellLineToDiseaseOrPhenotypicFeatureAssociation
classes.description: An relationship between a cell line and a disease or a phenotype, where the cell line is derived from an individual with that disease or phenotype.

classes.name: ChemicalEntityToEntityAssociationMixin
classes.description: An interaction between a chemical entity and another entity

classes.name: DrugToEntityAssociationMixin
classes.description: An interaction between a drug and another entity

classes.name: ChemicalToEntityAssociationMixin
classes.description: An interaction between a chemical entity and another entity

classes.name: CaseToEntityAssociationMixin
classes.description: An abstract association for use where the case is the subject

classes.name: ChemicalToChemicalAssociation
classes.description: A relationship between two chemical entities. This can encompass actual interactions as well as temporal causal edges, e.g. one chemical converted to another.

classes.name: ChemicalToChemicalDerivationAssociation
classes.description:
A causal relationship between two chemical entities, where the subject represents the upstream entity and the object represents the downstream. For any such association there is an implicit reaction:
  IF
  R has-input C1 AND
  R has-output C2 AND
  R enabled-by P AND
  R type Reaction
  THEN
  C1 derives-into C2 <<catalyst qualifier P>>

classes.name: ChemicalToDiseaseOrPhenotypicFeatureAssociation
classes.description: An interaction between a chemical entity and a phenotype or disease, where the presence of the chemical gives rise to or exacerbates the phenotype.

classes.name: ChemicalOrDrugOrTreatmentToDiseaseOrPhenotypicFeatureAssociation
classes.description: This association defines a relationship between a chemical or treatment (or procedure) and a disease or phenotypic feature where the disesae or phenotypic feature is a secondary undesirable effect.

classes.name: ChemicalOrDrugOrTreatmentSideEffectDiseaseOrPhenotypicFeatureAssociation
classes.description: This association defines a relationship between a chemical or treatment (or procedure) and a disease or phenotypic feature where the disesae or phenotypic feature is a secondary, typically (but not always) undesirable effect.

classes.name: GeneToPathwayAssociation
classes.description: An interaction between a gene or gene product and a biological process or pathway.

classes.name: MolecularActivityToPathwayAssociation
classes.description: Association that holds the relationship between a reaction and the pathway it participates in.

classes.name: ChemicalToPathwayAssociation
classes.description: An interaction between a chemical entity and a biological process or pathway.

classes.name: ChemicalGeneInteractionAssociation
classes.description: describes a physical interaction between a chemical entity and a gene or gene product. Any biological or chemical effect resulting from such an interaction are out of scope, and covered by the ChemicalAffectsGeneAssociation type (e.g. impact of a chemical on the abundance, activity, structure, etc, of either participant in the interaction)

classes.name: ChemicalAffectsGeneAssociation
classes.description: Describes an effect that a chemical has on a gene or gene product (e.g. an impact of on its abundance, activity, localization, processing, expression, etc.)

classes.name: DrugToGeneAssociation
classes.description: An interaction between a drug and a gene or gene product.

classes.name: MaterialSampleToEntityAssociationMixin
classes.description: An association between a material sample and something.

classes.name: MaterialSampleDerivationAssociation
classes.description: An association between a material sample and the material entity from which it is derived.

classes.name: MaterialSampleToDiseaseOrPhenotypicFeatureAssociation
classes.description: An association between a material sample and a disease or phenotype.

classes.name: EntityToExposureEventAssociationMixin
classes.description: An association between some entity and an exposure event.

classes.name: DiseaseToExposureEventAssociation
classes.description: An association between an exposure event and a disease.

classes.name: EntityToOutcomeAssociationMixin
classes.description: An association between some entity and an outcome

classes.name: ExposureEventToOutcomeAssociation
classes.description: An association between an exposure event and an outcome.

classes.name: FrequencyQualifierMixin
classes.description: Qualifier for frequency type associations

classes.name: EntityToFeatureOrDiseaseQualifiersMixin
classes.description: Qualifiers for entity to disease or phenotype associations.

classes.name: InformationContentEntityToNamedThingAssociation
classes.description: association between a named thing and a information content entity where the specific context of the relationship between that named thing and the publication is unknown. For example, model organisms databases often capture the knowledge that a gene is found in a journal article, but not specifically the context in which that gene was documented in the article. In these cases, this association with the accompanying predicate 'mentions' could be used. Conversely, for more specific associations (like 'gene to disease association', the publication should be captured as an edge property).

classes.name: EntityToDiseaseAssociationMixin
classes.description: mixin class for any association whose object (target node) is a disease

classes.name: DiseaseOrPhenotypicFeatureToLocationAssociation
classes.description: An association between either a disease or a phenotypic feature and an anatomical entity, where the disease/feature manifests in that site.

classes.name: DiseaseOrPhenotypicFeatureToGeneticInheritanceAssociation
classes.description: An association between either a disease or a phenotypic feature and its mode of (genetic) inheritance.

classes.name: GenotypeToPhenotypicFeatureAssociation
classes.description: Any association between one genotype and a phenotypic feature, where having the genotype confers the phenotype, either in isolation or through environment

classes.name: ExposureEventToPhenotypicFeatureAssociation
classes.description: Any association between an environment and a phenotypic feature, where being in the environment influences the phenotype.

classes.name: DiseaseToPhenotypicFeatureAssociation
classes.description: An association between a disease and a phenotypic feature in which the phenotypic feature is associated with the disease in some way.

classes.name: CaseToPhenotypicFeatureAssociation
classes.description: An association between a case (e.g. individual patient) and a phenotypic feature in which the individual has or has had the phenotype.

classes.name: BehaviorToBehavioralFeatureAssociation
classes.description: An association between an mixture behavior and a behavioral feature manifested by the individual exhibited or has exhibited the behavior.

classes.name: GeneToDiseaseAssociation
comments: NCIT:R176 refers to the inverse relationship

classes.name: VariantToGeneAssociation
classes.description: An association between a variant and a gene, where the variant has a genetic association with the gene (i.e. is in linkage disequilibrium)

classes.name: VariantToGeneExpressionAssociation
classes.description: An association between a variant and expression of a gene (i.e. e-QTL)

classes.name: VariantToPopulationAssociation
classes.description: An association between a variant and a population, where the variant has particular frequency in the population

classes.name: PopulationToPopulationAssociation
classes.description: An association between a two populations

classes.name: VariantToDiseaseAssociation
comments: TODO decide no how to model pathogenicity

classes.name: GenotypeToDiseaseAssociation
comments: TODO decide no how to model pathogenicity

classes.name: ModelToDiseaseAssociationMixin
classes.description: This mixin is used for any association class for which the subject (source node) plays the role of a 'model', in that it recapitulates some features of the disease in a way that is useful for studying the disease outside a patient carrying the disease

classes.name: GeneToExpressionSiteAssociation
classes.description: An association between a gene and a gene expression site, possibly qualified by stage/timing info.
notes: TBD: introduce subclasses for distinction between wild-type and experimental conditions?

classes.name: SequenceVariantModulatesTreatmentAssociation
classes.description: An association between a sequence variant and a treatment or health intervention. The treatment object itself encompasses both the disease and the drug used.
comments: An alternate way to model the same information could be via a qualifier

classes.name: FunctionalAssociation
classes.description: An association between a macromolecular machine mixin (gene, gene product or complex of gene products) and either a molecular activity, a biological process or a cellular location in which a function is executed.

classes.name: MacromolecularMachineToEntityAssociationMixin
classes.description: an association which has a macromolecular machine mixin as a subject

classes.name: MacromolecularMachineToMolecularActivityAssociation
classes.description: A functional association between a macromolecular machine (gene, gene product or complex) and a molecular activity (as represented in the GO molecular function branch), where the entity carries out the activity, or contributes to its execution.

classes.name: MacromolecularMachineToBiologicalProcessAssociation
classes.description: A functional association between a macromolecular machine (gene, gene product or complex) and a biological process or pathway (as represented in the GO biological process branch), where the entity carries out some part of the process, regulates it, or acts upstream of it.

classes.name: MacromolecularMachineToCellularComponentAssociation
classes.description: A functional association between a macromolecular machine (gene, gene product or complex) and a cellular component (as represented in the GO cellular component branch), where the entity carries out its function in the cellular component.

classes.name: MolecularActivityToChemicalEntityAssociation
classes.description: Added in response to capturing relationship between microbiome activities as measured via measurements of blood analytes as collected via blood and stool samples

classes.name: MolecularActivityToMolecularActivityAssociation
classes.description: Added in response to capturing relationship between microbiome activities as measured via measurements of blood analytes as collected via blood and stool samples

classes.name: SequenceAssociation
classes.description: An association between a sequence feature and a nucleic acid entity it is localized to.

classes.name: GenomicSequenceLocalization
classes.description: A relationship between a sequence feature and a nucleic acid entity it is localized to. The reference entity may be a chromosome, chromosome region or information entity such as a contig.

classes.name: SequenceFeatureRelationship
classes.description: For example, a particular exon is part of a particular transcript or gene

classes.name: TranscriptToGeneRelationship
classes.description: A gene is a collection of transcripts

classes.name: GeneToGeneProductRelationship
classes.description: A gene is transcribed and potentially translated to a gene product

classes.name: ExonToTranscriptRelationship
classes.description: A transcript is formed from multiple exons

classes.name: ChemicalEntityOrGeneOrGeneProductRegulatesGeneAssociation
classes.description: A regulatory relationship between two genes

classes.name: AnatomicalEntityToAnatomicalEntityPartOfAssociation
classes.description: A relationship between two anatomical entities where the relationship is mereological, i.e the two entities are related by parthood. This includes relationships between cellular components and cells, between cells and tissues, tissues and whole organisms

classes.name: AnatomicalEntityToAnatomicalEntityOntogenicAssociation
classes.description: A relationship between two anatomical entities where the relationship is ontogenic, i.e. the two entities are related by development. A number of different relationship types can be used to specify the precise nature of the relationship.

classes.name: OrganismTaxonToEntityAssociation
classes.description: An association between an organism taxon and another entity

classes.name: OrganismTaxonToOrganismTaxonAssociation
classes.description: A relationship between two organism taxon nodes

classes.name: OrganismTaxonToOrganismTaxonSpecialization
classes.description: A child-parent relationship between two taxa. For example: Homo sapiens subclass_of Homo

classes.name: OrganismTaxonToOrganismTaxonInteraction
classes.description: An interaction relationship between two taxa. This may be a symbiotic relationship (encompassing mutualism and parasitism), or it may be non-symbiotic. Example: plague transmitted_by flea; cattle domesticated_by Homo sapiens; plague infects Homo sapiens
